concept_explanation.intro:
**Composition** is when a class has another class as a FIELD. It models the 'has-a' relationship:

- A `Car` **has-a** `Engine`
- An `Order` **has-a** `Customer`
- A `Library` **has-a** `Catalog` of Books
- A `University` **has-a** `Faculty` of Professors

Implementation:

```java
class Engine {
    private int horsepower;
    private String type;  // 'V6', 'Electric', etc.

    public Engine(int horsepower, String type) {
        this.horsepower = horsepower;
        this.type = type;
    }

    // getters, toString...
}

class Car {
    private String make;
    private String model;
    private Engine engine;  // composition — has-a Engine

    public Car(String make, String model, Engine engine) {
        this.make = make;
        this.model = model;
        this.engine = engine;
    }

    public Engine getEngine() { return engine; }
    // getters, toString...
}

// Usage:
Engine v6 = new Engine(300, "V6");
Car bmw = new Car("BMW", "3-Series", v6);
System.out.println(bmw.getEngine().getHorsepower());  // 300
```

A Car IS NOT an Engine. A Car HAS an Engine. That's the distinction. Composition always models 'has-a.'

concept_explanation.objects_as_fields:
The field can be any type — a class you define, a class from the library, even the same class:

```java
class Person {
    private String name;
    private Address address;    // custom class
    private List<String> hobbies;  // library class (covered in Collections)
    private Person spouse;      // same class! (can be null if single)
}

class Address {
    private String street;
    private String city;
    private String zip;
    // constructor, getters, toString, equals, hashCode...
}
```

**Default value**: if an object field isn't initialized, it's `null`. Calling methods on null throws NullPointerException.

**Defensive practice**: initialize object fields in the constructor:

```java
class Person {
    private String name;
    private Address address;  // might be null

    public Person(String name, Address address) {
        this.name = name;
        this.address = address;  // could be null — caller's choice
    }

    public String getCity() {
        if (address == null) return "Unknown";
        return address.getCity();  // only call if not null
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.arrays_of_objects_in_classes:
Classes often contain ARRAYS of other objects (before we have ArrayList):

```java
class Course {
    private String courseName;
    private Student[] enrolledStudents;
    private int studentCount;

    public Course(String courseName, int maxStudents) {
        this.courseName = courseName;
        this.enrolledStudents = new Student[maxStudents];
        this.studentCount = 0;
    }

    public void enroll(Student s) {
        if (studentCount < enrolledStudents.length) {
            enrolledStudents[studentCount++] = s;
        }
    }

    public Student[] getEnrolled() {
        // Return a copy to protect internal state
        return Arrays.copyOf(enrolledStudents, studentCount);
    }
}
```

Notice the `getEnrolled()` returns a COPY via `Arrays.copyOf`. This is **defensive copying** — prevents external code from modifying the internal array.

**The count + array pattern**: always track how many elements are actually used vs the array's total capacity.

concept_explanation.chaining_method_calls:
With composition, you can chain method calls:

```java
Order order = ...;
String city = order.getShippingAddress().getCity();
int zip = order.getCustomer().getAddress().getZip();
```

But be careful — if ANY step returns null, you get NullPointerException:

```java
// Unsafe if any link could be null:
order.getCustomer().getAddress().getCity()

// Safer:
Customer customer = order.getCustomer();
if (customer != null) {
    Address addr = customer.getAddress();
    if (addr != null) {
        String city = addr.getCity();
    }
}
```

Realistically: good class design with validated constructors means you rarely encounter null chains in the middle. The defensive null checks are insurance.

**'Demeter's Law'** (informally): 'don't talk to strangers.' Avoid long chains. `order.getCustomerCity()` is better than `order.getCustomer().getAddress().getCity()` — it hides the internal structure.

concept_explanation.composition_full_example:
A complete, properly encapsulated multi-class design:

```java
class Address {
    private final String street;
    private final String city;
    private final String zip;

    public Address(String street, String city, String zip) {
        this.street = street;
        this.city = city;
        this.zip = zip;
    }

    public String getStreet() { return street; }
    public String getCity() { return city; }
    public String getZip() { return zip; }

    @Override
    public String toString() { 
        return street + ", " + city + " " + zip;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (!(o instanceof Address)) return false;
        Address a = (Address) o;
        return Objects.equals(street, a.street)
            && Objects.equals(city, a.city)
            && Objects.equals(zip, a.zip);
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(street, city, zip);
    }
}

class Customer {
    private static int nextId = 1;
    private final int id;
    private String name;
    private Address address;  // composition

    public Customer(String name, Address address) {
        this.id = nextId++;
        this.name = name;
        this.address = address;
    }

    public int getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public Address getAddress() { return address; }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Customer[#" + id + " " + name + " @ " + address + "]";
    }
}
```

Every concept from Topics 4.1-4.5 in action:
- Classes (4.1)
- Constructors with validation (4.2)
- Encapsulation, private fields (4.3)
- toString, equals, hashCode (4.4)
- Static counter, static final (4.5)
- PLUS: composition (Address inside Customer) — 4.6

concept_explanation.module4_synthesis:
Module 4 covered SIX topics:

**4.1 Classes & Objects**: Classes bundle data + behavior. Objects are instances. Dot notation. Reference semantics.

**4.2 Constructors**: Initialize objects properly. `this` keyword. Overloading, chaining with `this(...)`. Validation.

**4.3 Encapsulation**: Private fields, public getters/setters with validation. Immutable fields. Access control.

**4.4 Object Methods**: toString, equals, hashCode. The @Override annotation. The equals/hashCode contract.

**4.5 Static Members**: Static fields, constants, utility methods, factory methods. Singleton pattern.

**4.6 Composition**: Classes containing other classes. Has-a relationships. Multi-class system design.

A properly designed Java class uses ALL of these:

```java
class Employee {                          // 4.1 — class
    private static int nextId = 1;        // 4.5 — static counter
    public static final int MAX_SALARY = 9999999;  // 4.5 — constant

    private final int id;                 // 4.3 — private final
    private String name;                  // 4.3 — private
    private double salary;                // 4.3 — private
    private Address address;              // 4.6 — composition

    public Employee(String name, double salary, Address address) { // 4.2 — constructor
        if (name == null || name.isBlank()) throw new IllegalArgumentException();  // 4.2 validation
        if (salary < 0 || salary > MAX_SALARY) throw new IllegalArgumentException();
        this.id = nextId++;               // 4.5 — uses static field
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
        this.address = address;
    }

    public static int getTotalEmployees() { return nextId - 1; }  // 4.5 — static method

    public String getName() { return name; }          // 4.3 — getter
    public double getSalary() { return salary; }      // 4.3 — getter
    public Address getAddress() { return address; }   // 4.6 — composition getter

    public void setSalary(double salary) {            // 4.3 — validating setter
        if (salary < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException();
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    @Override public String toString() {              // 4.4
        return "Employee[#" + id + " " + name + "]"; 
    }

    @Override public boolean equals(Object o) {       // 4.4
        if (!(o instanceof Employee)) return false;
        return this.id == ((Employee) o).id;
    }

    @Override public int hashCode() {                // 4.4
        return Objects.hash(id);
    }
}
```

This is professional Java. Every pattern from every Module 4 topic, working together.

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
class Transaction {
    public static final String CREDIT = "CREDIT";
    public static final String DEBIT = "DEBIT";

    private final double amount;
    private final String type;         // CREDIT or DEBIT
    private final String description;

    public Transaction(double amount, String type, String description) {
        if (amount <= 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be positive");
        if (!type.equals(CREDIT) && !type.equals(DEBIT)) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid type: " + type);
        }
        this.amount = amount;
        this.type = type;
        this.description = description;
    }

    public double getAmount() { return amount; }
    public String getType() { return type; }
    public String getDescription() { return description; }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return type + ": ₹" + amount + " (" + description + ")";
    }
}
```

Immutable: all fields `final`, no setters. Valid states enforced at construction. Constants for CREDIT/DEBIT make code readable.

```java
class Customer {
    private static int nextId = 1;

    private final int id;
    private String name;
    private String email;

    public Customer(String name, String email) {
        if (name == null || name.isBlank()) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name required");
        if (email == null || !email.contains("@")) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Valid email required");
        this.id = nextId++;
        this.name = name;
        this.email = email;
    }

    public int getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public String getEmail() { return email; }

    public void setEmail(String email) {
        if (email == null || !email.contains("@")) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Valid email required");
        this.email = email;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Customer[#" + id + " " + name + " <" + email + ">]";
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (!(o instanceof Customer)) return false;
        return this.id == ((Customer) o).id;
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() { return Objects.hash(id); }
}
```

```java
class BankAccount {
    private static int nextAccountNumber = 1000;

    private final int accountNumber;
    private final Customer owner;           // COMPOSITION — has-a Customer
    private double balance;
    private final Transaction[] history;    // COMPOSITION — has-many Transactions
    private int transactionCount;

    public BankAccount(Customer owner, double initialBalance) {
        if (owner == null) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Owner required");
        if (initialBalance < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Initial balance cannot be negative");

        this.accountNumber = nextAccountNumber++;
        this.owner = owner;
        this.balance = initialBalance;
        this.history = new Transaction[100];
        this.transactionCount = 0;
    }

    public void credit(double amount, String description) {
        Transaction t = new Transaction(amount, Transaction.CREDIT, description);
        balance += amount;
        history[transactionCount++] = t;
    }

    public void debit(double amount, String description) {
        if (amount > balance) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Insufficient funds");
        Transaction t = new Transaction(amount, Transaction.DEBIT, description);
        balance -= amount;
        history[transactionCount++] = t;
    }

    public int getAccountNumber() { return accountNumber; }
    public Customer getOwner() { return owner; }
    public double getBalance() { return balance; }

    public Transaction[] getHistory() {
        return Arrays.copyOf(history, transactionCount);  // defensive copy!
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "BankAccount[#" + accountNumber + " owner=" + owner.getName() + ", balance=₹" + balance + "]";
    }
}
```

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Customer aisha = new Customer("Aisha Khan", "aisha@gmail.com");
    BankAccount account = new BankAccount(aisha, 5000.0);

    System.out.println(account);
    System.out.println("Owner: " + account.getOwner());

    account.credit(2000, "Salary");
    account.debit(500, "Grocery");
    account.debit(1200, "Rent");

    System.out.println("\nAfter transactions: " + account);
    System.out.println("\nTransaction History:");
    for (Transaction t : account.getHistory()) {
        System.out.println("  " + t);
    }
}
```

The method call chain: `account.getOwner()` returns the Customer object. `account.getHistory()` returns an array of Transaction objects. Every layer is a real object with its own behavior.

